<section class="card">
  <h2>About Garlic</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Fall-planted crop—establish before freeze, harvested the following summer.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Garlic is frost-hardy once established and is typically planted in fall.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), garlic viability depends less on finishing before first frost and more on establishing roots before sustained freezing, then accumulating enough seasonal heat the following year to size bulbs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Garlic does not follow a single-season “last frost to first frost” maturity pattern like most vegetables. Instead, it bridges two frost boundaries: fall establishment before freeze-up and summer harvest before the next fall frost cycle.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting window:</strong> Fall, typically 2–4 weeks before consistent ground freeze</li>
    <li><strong>Harvest:</strong> Mid to late summer the following year</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> ~240–300 days (multi-season)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Hardy once established</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    Garlic planning is frost-anchored but does not rely on a single frost-free window.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Fall Establishment Model</h2>

  <p>
    The goal of fall planting is root establishment before deep freeze. Garlic does not need top growth before winter; it needs time in workable soil before temperatures consistently drop below freezing.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Too early:</strong> Excess top growth before winter</li>
    <li><strong>On time:</strong> Root establishment before freeze, minimal top growth</li>
    <li><strong>Too late:</strong> Insufficient root system before sustained freeze</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a> to anchor fall planting relative to your first frost and typical freeze progression.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For a deeper explanation of frost probability and boundaries, see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Tolerance & Winter Survival</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Freeze tolerance:</strong> Established cloves tolerate sub-freezing winter soil</li>
    <li><strong>Mulch:</strong> Often used in cold climates to stabilize soil temperature</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C) marks freeze onset, not crop termination</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Once rooted, garlic is winter-hardy in most cold-climate regions. The risk is not frost kill, but poor establishment if planted too late.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring & Summer Heat Accumulation</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C) for heat-budget comparison</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed (spring–summer):</strong> ~1,200–1,800 GDD (base 50) to size bulbs, depending on type and climate</p>

  <p>
    After winter dormancy, garlic resumes growth in spring. Bulb development depends on accumulated seasonal heat and day length.
    Weak heat accumulation in spring and early summer can delay sizing and reduce bulb size.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    To understand how frost boundaries and heat accumulation interact across seasons, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice in short summers?</strong> Yes (because growth begins early in spring)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky in extremely short frost-free windows?</strong> Rarely; garlic’s multi-season model reduces risk</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Usually no; mulch may stabilize soil temperatures</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Garlic is not terminated by fall frost once established. The 32°F (0°C) boundary is relevant primarily for timing fall planting and understanding when soil begins freezing—not for harvest cutoff.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Plant early enough in fall for root establishment before freeze</li>
    <li>Use mulch in colder climates to stabilize soil temperature</li>
    <li>Select varieties adapted to your climate (hardneck vs softneck)</li>
    <li>Ensure full sun in spring to maximize effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Fall Frost Boundary → Winter Survival → Spring Heat Accumulation → Bulb Development → Summer Harvest
  </p>

  <p>
    Garlic differs from most crops because it bridges two seasons. In a typical year, viability depends on successful fall establishment and sufficient spring–summer heat to size bulbs before harvest.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can garlic survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Established garlic is winter-hardy and tolerates freezing conditions in most cold-climate regions.
  </p>

  <h3>Does garlic need to mature before first frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Garlic is planted before winter and harvested the following summer. First frost is not a harvest cutoff.
  </p>

  <h3>What happens if garlic is planted too late?</h3>
  <p>
    Late planting may prevent proper root establishment before sustained freeze, increasing winter survival risk.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) frost timing to anchor fall planting (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Garlic is multi-season and winter-hardy once established.</li>
    <li>Spring–summer heat accumulation determines bulb size.</li>
    <li>Model viability using fall establishment + seasonal heat budget + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>